	</subsection>

	<subsection xml:id="ss-3-4-another-example">
		<title>Another example</title>

		<p>
			Let's do another example for practice. Suppose instead we want to know when health care costs would exceed $10 trillion instead. (By the way - wow!) That means <m>H = 10</m>. Using our equation <m>H=2.26\ast1.067^Y</m> we get 
			<me>2.26\ast1.067^Y=10</me>. 
			Opposite steps in the opposite order: first we should divide boty sides by 2.26.
			<me>\frac{\cancel{2.26}\ast1.067^Y}{\cancel{2.26}}=\frac{10}{2.26}=10 \div 2.26 = 4.424778761\ldots</me> 
			That means 
			<me>1.067^Y=4.424778761\ldots</me> 
			Now our equation fits the format <m>g^Y=v</m> for the <xref ref="log-divides-formula" text="title"/> with new value <m>v=4.424778761\ldots</m> (and the growth factor is <m>g=1.067</m> still). So the answer is
			<md>
				<mrow>Y \amp = \frac{\log (v)}{\log(g)} </mrow>
				<mrow> \amp = \frac{\log (4.424778761\ldots)}{\log(1.067)} </mrow>
				<mrow> \amp = \log (4.424778761\ldots) \div \log (1.067) </mrow>
				<mrow> \amp = 22.932891 \approx 23  </mrow>
			</md> 
			Want to avoid typing in the number 4.424778761<ellipsis/>? Depending on your calculator, you might try this instead: <me>10 \div 2.26 = \log(\text{ANS}) \div \log(1.067)= 22.932891</me> where <term>ANS</term> stands for <q>answer</q>.
		</p>

		<p>
			Again that means 23 years after 2007, or 2007 + 23 = 2030. Health care costs are projected to exceed $10 trillion in the year 2030. Well, unless we do something about that. (Helps explain why government folks are often discussing how to contain health care costs.)
		</p>

		<figure xml:id="3-4-healthcare-costs-10">
			<caption>
				<m>H</m> = health care costs, as a function of <m>Y</m> = years since 2007
